t= PDF|accessdate=30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Education ==

[[Image:S3010334-cropped.jpg|thumb|left|[[The Kings of Wessex School]] seen from the tower of St. Andrew's Church (looking north-west)]]
Cheddar has three schools belonging to the Cheddar Valley Group of Schools, twelve schools that provide Cheddar Valley's [[three-tier education]] system.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.markfirstschool.ik.org/documents/1086325389.ikml#sbt8 | publisher= Mark First School | title= Prospectus | accessdate=5 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; Cheddar First School has ten classes for children between 4 and 9 years.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cheddarfirst.ik.org/|title=Cheddar First School|publisher=Cheddar First School|accessdate=30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Fairlands Middle School]], a [[middle school]] categorised as a middle-deemed-secondary school, has 510 pupils between 9 and 13.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://slp2.somerset.gov.uk/schools/fms/Site%20Pages/About%20the%20School.aspx|title=School Profile|publisher=Fairlands Middle School|accessdate=5 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; Fairlands takes children moving up from Cheddar First School as well as other first schools in the Cheddar Valley. [[The Kings of Wessex School]], a coeducational [[comprehensive school]], has been rated as &quot;outstanding&quot; by [[Ofsted]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url= http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_reports/display/(id)/117057 | title= The Kings of Wessex School Inspection report | publisher= [[Ofsted]] | date= 1 March 2010 | accessdate= 2 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; It has 1,182 students aged 13 to 18,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_providers/full/(urn)/123896|title=The Kings of Wessex School|publisher=[[Ofsted]]|accessdate=27 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; including 302 in the [[sixth form]]. Kings is a [[faith school]] linked to the [[Church of England]]. It was awarded the [[Specialist school|specialist status]] of [[Technology College]] in 2001, enabling it to develop its [[Information Technology]] (IT) facilities and improve courses in science, mathematics and design technology. In 2007 it became a [[foundation school]], giving it more control over its own finances. The school owns and runs a sports centre and swimming pool, Kings Fitness &amp; Leisure, with facilities that are used by students as well as residents. Community education project I.T. for the Terrified, which was originally set up in Wedmore in 1999,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2886013.stm |publisher= BBC News | date= 25 March 2003 | title= Village's cyber cafe opens
 | accessdate= 27 January 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; is based in an old cow shed on the school's grounds.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal | url= http://www.kowessex.co.uk/downloads/newsletters/kings_messenger_86.pdf | format= PDF | title= Kings Messenger | volume= Issue 86 | publisher= [[The Kings of Wessex School]] | year= 2009 | month= July | accessdate= 27 January 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Religious sites ==

[[File:Cheddarchurch.jpg|thumb|[[Church of St Andrew, Cheddar|Church of St Andrew]]]]
The [[Church of St Andrew, Cheddar|Church of St Andrew]] dates from the 14th&amp;nbsp;century. It was restored in 1873 by [[William Butterfield]]. It is a Grade&amp;nbsp;I [[listed building]] and contains some 15th-century [[stained glass]] and an altar table of 1631. The [[church monument|chest tomb]] in the chancel is believed to contain the remains of Sir [[Thomas Cheddar]] and is dated 1442.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| title=Church of St. Andrew | work=[[Images of England]] | publisher=[[English Heritage]] | url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?id=268768 | accessdate=9 May 2006}}&lt;/ref&gt; The tower, which rises to {{convert|100|ft|m|0}},&lt;ref name=&quot;curio&quot;&gt;{{Cite book|title=Curiosities of Somerset |last=Leete-Hodge |first=Lornie |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1985 |publisher=Bossiney Books |location=Bodmin |isbn=0906456983 |page=20 }}&lt;/ref&gt; contains a bell dating from 1759 made by Thomas Bilbie of the [[Bilbie family]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|last=Moore |first=James |authorlink= |url=|coauthors=Roy Rice &amp; Ernest Hucker |title=Bilbie and the Chew Valley clock makers |year=1995 |pages= |publisher=The authors |location= |isbn= }}&lt;/ref&gt;

There are also churches for [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]], [[Methodism|Methodist]] and other denominations, including Cheddar Valley Community Church, who not only meet at The Kings of Wessex School on Sunday, but also have their own site on Tweentown for meeting during the week.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cheddarvalleycommunitychurch.org/|title=Cheddar Valley Community Church|publisher=Cheddar Valley Community Church|accessdate=30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[Baptist]] chapel was built in 1831.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/Details/Default.aspx?id=268783|title=Baptist Chapel|work=[[Images of England]]|publisher=[[English Heritage]]|accessdate=30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Sport ==

Kings Fitness &amp; Leisure, situated on the grounds of [[The Kings of Wessex School]], provides a venue for various sports and includes a 20-metre swimming pool, racket sport courts, a sports hall, dance studios and a gym.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cheddarvillage.co.uk/Sport_Leisure/index.htm|title=Sport and Leisure|publisher=Cheddar Web Site|accessdate=30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; A youth sports festival was held on Sharpham Road Playing Fields in 2009.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://cheddaryouthsports.co.uk/|title=Cheddar Youth Sports Festival |publisher=Cheddar Youth Sports Festival |accessdate=30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 2010 a [[skatepark]] was built in the village,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| newspaper= Cheddar Valley Gazette | url= http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/shepton/news/Skate-park-man-appears-TV/article-1784459-detail/article.html | title= Skate park man appears on TV | date= 1 February 2010 | accessdate= 30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; funded by the Cheddar Local Action Team.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news| url= http://www.thewestonmercury.co.uk/news/lions_pledge_skate_help_1_312349| newspaper= The Weston Mercury | title= Lions pledge skate help | date= 9 July 2007|accessdate=31 January 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Cheddar Football Club, founded in 1892 and nicknamed &quot;The Cheesemen&quot;,&lt;ref name=&quot;football&quot;&gt;{{Cite news|url=http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/news/Cheddar-Football-Club-premises/article-1031461-detail/article.html|title=Cheddar Football Club could move premises|date=28 May 2009|newspaper= Cheddar Valley Gazette|accessdate=30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; play in the [[Somerset County Football League]] Premier Division.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cheddarfc.co.uk/|title=Cheddar AFC|publisher=Cheddar AFC|accessdate=30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 2009 plans were revealed to move the club from its present home at Bowdens Park on Draycott Road to a new larger site.&lt;ref name=&quot;football&quot;/&gt;

Cheddar Cricket Club was formed in the late 19th&amp;nbsp;century and moved to Sharpham Road Playing Fields in 1964.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cheddarcc.co.uk/history.html|title=History|publisher=Cheddar Cricket Club|accessdate=30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; They now play in the [[West of England Premier League]] Somerset Division. Cheddar Rugby Club organises an annual Cheddar Rugby Tournament.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cheddar-rugby.co.uk/home.asp|title=Cheddar Rugby Club|publisher=Cheddar Rugby Club|accessdate=5 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; Cheddar [[Lawn Tennis]] Club, was formed in 1924,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cheddartennisclub.co.uk/history.html|title=History|publisher=Cheddar Tennis Club|accessdate=30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; and play in the North Somerset League and also has social tennis and coaching. Cheddar Running Club organised an annual [[half marathon]] until 2009.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cheddarrunningclub.co.uk/half_marathon/21__last_cheddar_half_marathon.html|title=Last Cheddar Half Marathon|publisher=Cheddar Running Club|date= 1 December 2009 |accessdate=30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

