'''Caelum''' is a faint [[constellation]] in the southern sky, introduced in the 18th century by [[Nicolas Louis de Lacaille]]. Its name means &quot;the [[chisel]]&quot; in [[Latin]], and it was formerly known as '''Cæla Sculptoris''', &quot;the sculptor's chisel&quot;. It is the eighth smallest constellation, with an area just less than that of [[Corona Australis]].

== Notable features ==
{{See also|List of stars in Caelum}}
Caelum is a faint constellation, having no star brighter than fourth magnitude.  Its brightest star is the magnitude 4.45 [[Alpha Caeli|α Caeli]].   

A small telescope splits [[Gamma Caeli|γ Caeli]] into a magnitude 4.5 red giant and a magnitude 6.34 white giant.  Larger telescopes are needed to see several [[New General Catalog|NGC]] objects, all galaxies, but none brighter than magnitude 11.5 or larger than 3 arcminutes.&lt;ref&gt;[http://seds.org/Maps/Stars_en/Fig/caelum.html Caelum at SEDS.org]&lt;/ref&gt;

Most notable galaxies are NGC 1571, NGC 1679 and IC 2106.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.wingmakers.co.nz/universe/constellations/Caelum.html Caelum]&lt;/ref&gt;

==Namesakes==
[[USS Caelum (AK-106)]] was a [[United States Navy]] ship named after the constellation.

