    <title>Cow tipping</title>
    <id>6520</id>
    <revision>
      <id>431115570</id>
      <timestamp>2011-05-27T02:36:10Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>Slightsmile</username>
        <id>11737418</id>
      </contributor>
      <minor />
      <comment>[[Help:Reverting|Reverted]] edits by [[Special:Contributions/202.45.119.68|202.45.119.68]] ([[User talk:202.45.119.68|talk]]) to last version by Ohnoitsjamie</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">[[File:Tipped cow 2008-07-05 14-29-2.jpg|right|thumb|300px|A cow lying on its side]]

'''Cow tipping''' or '''cow pushing''' is the purported activity of sneaking up on a sleeping, upright [[Cattle|cow]] and pushing it over for fun. As cattle do not sleep standing up, cow tipping is a myth.&lt;ref name=Cow1/&gt;

==Myth and reality==
According to the myth, cattle can easily be pushed over without much force because they are slow-moving, slow-witted and weak-legged, have a high center of gravity and sleep standing up. However, numerous publications have debunked cow-tipping as a myth. Cattle only doze while standing up, instead of sleeping, and are easily disturbed.&lt;ref name = Cow1&gt;{{cite news|last = Malvern|first = Jack|title = Cow-tipping myth hasn't got a leg to stand on|publisher = Times Online|url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2-1858246,00.html|accessdate = 2006-10-28 | location=London | date=November 5, 2005}}&lt;/ref&gt; Also, they represent over half a ton of weight that would easily resist lesser force. A variety of calculations have been performed to determine if cow tipping is physically possible.&lt;ref name = Cow1/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|last = Semke|first = Matt|title = The Statics of Cow Tipping|publisher = UNL College of Engineering and Mechanics Course Project|url = http://emweb.unl.edu/Mechanics-Pages/Matt-Semke/The%20Statics%20of%20Cow%20Tipping.htm|accessdate = 2007-04-17}}&lt;/ref&gt; A study led by Margo Lillie, a doctor of [[zoology]] at the [[University of British Columbia]], concludes that cow tipping by a single person is impossible. Her calculations found that it would take at least two people to apply enough force to push over a cow if the cow does not react and reorient its footing. If the cow does react, it would take at least four people to push it over. Professor Lillie noted that, contrary to the myth, cattle are well aware of their surroundings (they have excellent senses of smell and hearing) and are very difficult to sneak up on.&lt;ref name = Cow1/&gt;&lt;ref name = &quot;Debunk&quot;&gt;{{Cite news|last = Colebourn|first = John|title = Debunking rural myth of cow tipping: It's udder nonsense, academics contend|newspaper = Montreal Gazette|pages = A10|date = November 9, 2005|url=|postscript = &lt;!--None--&gt;}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.gazette.uwo.ca/article.cfm?section=FrontPage&amp;articleID=465&amp;month=11&amp;day=9&amp;year=2005 Cow-tipping a mooo-yth?] by Ian Denomme, The Gazette (Western Daily Student Newspaper), November 9, 2005. (retrieved on January 12, 2009)&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://tahlequahdailypress.com/archive/x519330324 Cow-tipping: Myth or reality?] by Eddie Glenn, Tahlequah Daily Press, December 15, 2006. (retrieved on January 12, 2009).&lt;/ref&gt;

The British media outlet ''[[Times Online]]'' has posted a detailed illustration of the force necessary to push over a cow.&lt;ref&gt;[http://images.thetimes.co.uk/TGD/picture/0,,242244,00.jpg Happy Torque - Force Required to Tip over a cow] at the Time Online.&lt;/ref&gt;

Horses, on the other hand, regularly sleep standing up, due to a locking mechanism of their [[stifle joint]], a trait cows do not possess.

==History==
[[Julius Caesar]] and [[Pliny]] record a belief that European [[moose]] had no knee joints and could not get up if they fell over.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book | publisher = Harper &amp; brothers | last = Caesar | first = Julius | coauthors = Aulus Hirtius | title = Caesar's Commentaries on the Gallic and civil wars | chapter = XXVII | page = 154 | year = 1879 | isbn = 0217452876 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/10657/pg10657.txt&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | title = Pliny the Elder, The Natural History (eds. John Bostock, M.D., F.R.S., H.T. Riley, Esq., B.A.) | accessdate = 2009-11-08 | url = http://old.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?lookup=Plin.+Nat.+8.16 }}&lt;/ref&gt; This belief may relate to the ancient custom of trapping moose in steep-sided pits. 

In 1255, [[Louis IX of France]] [[Sandwich, Kent#History|gave an elephant]] to [[Henry III of England]] for his [[menagerie]] in the [[Tower of London]]. Drawn from life by the historian [[Matthew Paris]] for his [[Chronica Majora]], it can be seen in his [[bestiary]] at [[Parker Library]] of [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], with an accompanying text revealing that at the time, Europeans believed that elephants did not have [[knee]]s and so were unable to get up if they fell over. The bestiary contains a drawing depicting an elephant on its back being dragged along the ground by another elephant, with a caption stating that elephants lacked knees.&lt;ref&gt;Willene B. Clark, ''A medieval book of beasts'', [http://books.google.com/books?id=0olPRmCoE8MC&amp;pg=PA128&amp;lpg=PA128&amp;dq=caesar+moose+no+knees&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=NEsI8FXP7O&amp;sig=-wE_AWF80zeCaaI8Rl-cXjn3Aew&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=JwJwTITND92eOLPzwLAL&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;ct=result&amp;resnum=2&amp;ved=0CBUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false p.128]&lt;/ref&gt;

==News==
In April 2008, four men in [[Naples, Florida]], who were arrested for damaging a gate to a communications tower in an open field, told police deputies that they had gone into the field and tipped over a cow. However, police stated this was impossible because there were no cattle within several miles of the field.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.naplesnews.com/news/2008/apr/22/cow-tipping-excuse-doesnt-fly-4-arrested/ 'Cow tipping' excuse doesn't fly; 4 arrested], Naples Daily News, April 22, 2008 (retrieved on January 12, 2009).&lt;/ref&gt;

==Popular culture==
Cow-tipping has appeared in a variety of media and entertainment. In the popular computer role-playing game series ''[[Fallout (series)|Fallout]]'', and other games such as ''[[Ultima Online]]'' and ''[[Asheron's Call]]'', players can push over cattle. In the 2006 animated movie ''[[Barnyard (film)|Barnyard]]'', a group of tough talking cattle from New Jersey go &quot;boy-tipping&quot; in response to similar behavior against cattle.&lt;ref&gt;[http://video.aol.com/video-detail/barnyard-the-original-party-animals-cow-tippingboy-tipping/1630119529 AOL Video Home &gt;Barnyard: The Original Party Animals - Cow Tipping] at AOL.com.&lt;/ref&gt; In another 2006 animation movie, ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'', characters go &quot;tractor-tippin'&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0317219/quotes IMDB Memorable quotes for Cars (2006)]&lt;/ref&gt; In a 1994 episode of the popular animated television series ''[[Beavis and Butt-head]]'', the two titular characters, after watching a milk ad on television, set out to tip over a cow, only to result in [[Beavis]] being crushed when the cow falls on him.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.tv.com/beavis-and-butthead/cow-tipping/episode/58212/summary.html Beavis and Butthead], Season 4, episode 2, Cow Tipping, first aired March 15, 1994.&lt;/ref&gt; Cow-tipping is also featured in the 1989 black comedy ''[[Heathers]]''&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|last=Larew |first=John L. |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1990/11/8/cow-tipping-is-a-load-of-bull/ |title=Cow-Tipping is a Load of Bull &amp;#124; The Harvard Crimson |publisher=Thecrimson.com |date=1990-11-08 |accessdate=2010-10-08}}&lt;/ref&gt; as well as the 1995 [[Chris Farley]]-[[David Spade]] comedy film ''[[Tommy Boy]]''.

The Maryland Lottery/Bovines Unite,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://adweek.blogs.com/adfreak/2005/05/cows_tips_colle.html |title=AdFreak: Cows tip college student for Maryland lottery |publisher=Adweek.blogs.com |date=2005-05-13 |accessdate=2010-10-08}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://bovineunite.blogspot.com/ |title=Bovine Blog |publisher=Bovineunite.blogspot.com |date= |accessdate=2010-10-08}}&lt;/ref&gt; Famous Dave's restaurants (&quot;Angus with attitude&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|author=&amp;ldquo;&amp;rdquo; |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wB0k_IJbrCA |title=Famous Dave's TV Ad- People Tipping |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2010-10-08}}&lt;/ref&gt;) and Coffee Mate&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.guzer.com/videos/people_tipping.php |title=Cows Tipping People - Funny Video Clips |publisher=Guzer.com |date= |accessdate=2010-10-08}}&lt;/ref&gt; television ads have all featured cows engaged in people-tipping.  ''The Official Cow-Tippers Handbook'' by Red McCoy and Duke Rightious is another example of how this urban legend has seeped into popular culture.

